I grew up wanting to be like Willy Wonka. Was my favorite movie. He had so many projects he was working on at all times. The chocolate river, the fizzy lifting drink, the everlasting gobstopper. He was constantly perfecting and modifying. Wanting to create a sense of inspiration and wonder for others and he did. Everything he did he gave it his all. He made the world a more colorful and vibrant place. 

He taught me a lot. Even though he isn’t real, the ideas are.

The mind is powerful. It has the potential to be a gold mine. The possibilities really are endless. 

“If you want to view paradise, simply look around and view it. Anything you want to, do it. Want to change the world? There’s nothing to it.”

A couple portraits of my dad (@jrbarela1) from Easter. A friendly, free spirited, but strong Christian man. When I was in middle school he bought me my first guitar from a pawn shop and paid for my music lessons. When I was in high school he shared the 60’s music that helped form his youth with me. When I discovered Bob Dylan, specifically his early folk years, I thought I knew what I wanted to do with my life, become a songwriter and speak about meaningful things. Years later I started silversmithing, something I also picked up from him. I owe much of who I am today to this man right here. A meek man that doesn’t seek much attention but deserves it. Love you dad.

This is something I’ve wrestled with for a long time. There are serious consequences in sharing my faith publicly. Especially in the social climate we find ourselves in. I’m entirely independent and self employed. My wife and three kids rely on the income I’m able to provide. 

In 2021 I scored an ongoing business relationship with a pretty major retailer that would have benefitted my business dramatically, not only financially, but also in audience size. They cut ties with me after finding out about my opposition to blm in 2020 and the canceling that ensued. I was crushed. I looked up to this company for years and after 6-8 months of designing and working on our exclusive collection they abandoned the order a day before shipping. Though that was discouraging, my conscience wouldn’t allow me to shut up. 

My faith saved my life. It gave me true hope and a future. I owe everything to Jesus so why wouldn’t I want to share Him with others? No matter the cost, it’s my ultimate duty. Society won’t change until bold Christian’s decide to engage the world publicly, unashamed of their Lord. Everyone else brings their private views to the public square, why not us?

Being a dad is my greatest privilege. I don’t take it lightly. My life, to them, has influence beyond my understanding. Everything I do will help shape them in one way or another. It’s a great and sometimes unbearable weight. I fail in front of them often. Then I apologize. I attempt to do better the next day though I know I will never be the perfect father. I know what they see me do is more powerful than what they hear me say. I try not to discourage them. I do my best to build them up, to speak life over them. To discipline when needed and show grace and mercy when needed. I love them more than the world. My greatest hope in life, aside from remaining faithful to Jesus myself, is that they too will one day have an encounter like I have and give their lives fully to him. That’s my prayer. May the Lord capture them and keep them forever. 🙏🏼

McCall’s Pumpkin Patch 2023 ✨

One of my favorite traditions! Every year gets better and better because the kids enjoy it so much, and this year we really made the most of it. Arlo and Scout have been counting down the days for at least a month! 

We wore layers, packed plenty of food and water and spent a good 5 hours taking our sweet time, enjoying everything the Patch has to offer. Whittling this down to 1.5 minutes took forever- I had to cut out half the fun to make it fit! Being at McCall’s is definitely taking a break from reality. No rushing, nothing to do, nowhere to be. No worries, no emergencies, no chaos. Days like this to reset and be together are priceless, and I’m so grateful. 

Special shout to the *best dad ever* for playing hookie from work on Friday to make it happen!

Over the last couple of weeks I’ve been observing the conversation surrounding the events in the Middle East, specifically within the Christian context.

There are many in American evangelicalism that correlate biblical Israel with the modern state of Israel, and up until recently I was among them.

After rigorous study and questioning I began to realize that though this perspective is popular in America today, it is not the common understanding worldwide or throughout church history. 

How we define this word effects much of how we interpret scripture, and how we understand the world around us.

Sorry I’ve been so quiet on here for the past little while. There are a lot of reasons for it but one of the biggest is that I’ve been in transition mode preparing for the new year. 

My commitments with Towns and Bunkhouse, places where I sublease my silversmithing and podcasting studios, will be expiring at the end of the year and we thought it best to bring it all back home. 

For the better part of December I’ve been reworking a vacant room at my house to be my all-in-one workspace for the next little while. This is the start to my silversmithing corner. 

With this move I will also be suspending the weekly podcast and instead focus on short form content. 

It’s bittersweet, really.

On one hand, I’ll miss being in a busy place seeing friends and meeting new people. On the other hand, I’m glad to be consolidating so much of my work into one room (if I can manage 😅).

We’ll save a ton on overhead, an hours worth of driving per day, and my workflow will be much more efficient. 

I don’t see this as a permanent move but rather a consolidation for a later relaunch of something bigger and better. I have so many ideas already and can’t wait to share when the time is right. 

In the new year, you can expect more of some of the best goods around and content to match.

Thanks for sticking around! The best is yet to come. 🙏🏼

(A lesson I learned in 2023) I spent the last few days tuning my mind for the best possible 2024. I needed a reset after an overwhelming December. A lot to process, honestly. So much has already changed. Both of our businesses have moved locations switching up our daily routines and workflow. It’s been stressful and exhausting but also exciting. With all of that behind us and being mostly settled in the new workspace, I can tell already that I’ll be much more productive and mentally focused moving into the new year.

Though a bit late in life, I’m learning just how limited we all are. We all have a finite amount of time, energy, and resources and what I’m coming to understand is that I’ve not been using mine optimally. Keeping up with multiple spaces and other unnecessary excesses have ultimately resulted in unnecessary struggle and unsustainability. After reading through “Basic Economics” by Thomas Sowell, I began to realize I wasn’t managing my time, energy and resources as efficiently as I could have and it was coming at the cost of my family, friends and business. Not only that but I’m now beginning to notice the effect it’s had on my creative spirit in general. Work became less and less enjoyable. 

I tell my kids that work is just play for adults. Of course, I have the tremendous privilege of doing what I love for a living (thanks to you) but I also see that as a perspective to achieve no matter what field of work you’re in. Whether I’m actually making jewelry, taking photos, doing research, editing videos or writing captions I do my best to find the play in it.
